   "source": [
    "# Data Analysis with Pandas\n",
    "## PyIU Advanced Python Workshop\n",
    "\n",
    "Authors: Kristin Baker\n",
    "\n",
    "Last modified: 6/2/2026\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook covers some of the basic mechanics of working with Pandas Dataframes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "765043c4-297a-4ac8-9ca9-eb8423e6337d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Introduction to Pandas"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cb50f152-2526-4c95-8658-51f71a49575f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Pandas is a Python library that lets you work with tabular data easily. Pandas works similarly to an Excel spreadsheet in that you store, sort, manipulate, and analyze tabular data sets (e.g., rows and columns). \n",
    "\n",
    "As with everything, first we need to import pandas. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "59c72fc1-e5c8-415a-bae8-22cf4d9e0717",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "21624d9e-48d9-4c85-8224-96bf0abc20b6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are a couple of ways to make a data frame (df). First, we can add data from existing lists or arrays into a df. Let's generate a couple of random arrays. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "55f330f4-765f-4dfd-b60a-e0e842705db5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "np.random.seed(1240)\n",
    "arr1 = np.random.randint(low=1, high=1200, size=1000)\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(87)\n",
    "arr2 = np.random.randint(low=1, high=1200, size=1000)\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(2965)\n",
    "arr3 = np.random.randint(low=1, high=1200, size=1000)"
